# component-contracts — Agent Rules

These rules apply to every task in this repository. Read them before making any changes.

---

## Common workspace issues

If `pnpm install` throws `ERR_PNPM_WORKSPACE_PKG_NOT_FOUND`, the package name field has been corrupted. Fix with:

```bash
sed -i '' 's/"@component-contracts\/schema"/"@ds\/schema"/' packages/schema/package.json
sed -i '' 's/"@component-contracts\/contracts"/"@ds\/contracts"/' packages/contracts/package.json
```

All packages in this workspace use the `@ds/` scope. Never use `@component-contracts/`.

---

## Core principle

**Contracts are authored before implementations.** Never write a component implementation without a corresponding `.contract.json` in `packages/contracts/src/`. The contract is the source of truth. The implementation is derived from it.

---

## Visual source of truth

**Figma is the designated visual source of truth** for all platform implementations. Until Figma token sync is active, the React implementation in `apps/web` is the interim visual reference for web targets only.

- For web targets (`apps/web`, `apps/web-components`): match the React implementation visually unless a platform constraint prevents it. Deviations require justification in `docs/decisions.md`.
- For native targets (`apps/ios`, `apps/android`): follow platform conventions. The contract defines behavioral and token parity — not pixel-perfect visual matching.
- When Figma sync is active: all implementations validate against Figma, not against each other.

---

## Atomic Design

Structure all components according to Atomic Design:

- **Atoms** — single-purpose, no dependencies on other components (Button, Icon, Badge, Input)
- **Molecules** — composed of atoms, single responsibility (Accordion, SearchInput, FormField)
- **Organisms** — composed of molecules and atoms, complex UI sections (Header, DataTable, Form)

Directory structure:
```
apps/web/src/
  atoms/button/
  molecules/accordion/
apps/web-components/src/
  components/atoms/button/
  components/molecules/accordion/
```

Atoms never import molecules. Molecules never import organisms.

---

## Contracts

- One `.contract.json` per component in `packages/contracts/src/`
- Every contract must pass `pnpm validate` before implementation begins
- Contract `id` is kebab-case, matches the directory name
- `status` must be `draft` during initial authoring, promoted to `stable` only when implementation is complete and tested
- Token paths must reference semantic tokens only — never primitives (`brand.500` not `color.blue.500`)
- Token keys use camelCase — no hyphens (e.g. `textSize`, not `text-size`)
- Run `pnpm validate` after every contract change — never skip this
- After updating a contract, run `pnpm --filter @ds/contracts build` before running Storybook — otherwise stale compiled output will be served

---

## Tokens

- **Never use raw values in CSS.** Every value must reference a CSS custom property from `@ds/tokens`
- Custom properties follow the pattern `--ds-{token-path}` with dots replaced by hyphens
- If a value you need doesn't exist as a token, add it to `packages/tokens/src/` first, run `pnpm tokens:build`, then use it
- Never add one-off values to component CSS or style files

---

## Implementation — React (`apps/web`)

- Use `class-variance-authority` (CVA) for all variant-to-class mappings
- CVA variant keys must match contract prop names and values exactly
- Use `clsx` for conditional className merging
- Always use `forwardRef` — components must forward refs to their root DOM element
- Use semantic HTML
- For complex interaction patterns (accordion, dialog, tooltip), use Radix UI primitives. Never hand-roll focus trapping, keyboard navigation, or ARIA state management.
- Component files: `{name}.tsx`, `{name}.css`, `{name}.stories.tsx`, `index.ts`

---

## Implementation — Web Components (`apps/web-components`)

### Process (follow in order)
1. **Read the contract** — props, variants, behavior, accessibility, composition
2. **Define the custom elements** — one class per slot in the composition block
3. **Decide where state lives** — always the root element
4. **Wire coordination** — events bubble up, state pushes down via methods
5. **Apply token styles** — `CSSStyleSheet` + `adoptedStyleSheets`, all `var(--ds-*)` references
6. **Implement keyboard behavior** — `keydown` on the root, match `behavior.keyboardShortcuts` exactly
7. **Set ARIA** — match the `accessibility` block exactly

### Conventions
- File naming: `ds-{name}.ts` (e.g. `ds-button.ts`, `ds-accordion.ts`)
- Custom element names: `ds-{name}` (e.g. `<ds-button>`, `<ds-accordion>`)
- Register with: `customElements.define("ds-{name}", ClassName)`
- No framework, no library — pure `HTMLElement` only
- Styles inlined via `CSSStyleSheet` and `adoptedStyleSheets` — no external CSS files
- State coordination: custom DOM events bubble up to root, root pushes state down via methods
- Custom events use `ds-` prefix (e.g. `ds-press`, `ds-value-change`)
- Always set `bubbles: true, composed: true` on custom events so they cross shadow boundaries

### Visual parity
- The React implementation is the interim visual reference for web targets
- When implementing a web component, open the React Storybook alongside the web component demo and match them visually before considering the component done
- CSS structure should mirror the React component's CSS — same properties, same token references, same states

---

## Accessibility

- Every contract must declare `accessibility.wcagLevel` — minimum `AA`
- Every component must have a declared ARIA `role`
- Keyboard interactions must be listed in `behavior.keyboardShortcuts`
- The a11y panel must show 0 violations on all stories before merge
- Focus management must follow the contract's `accessibility.focusManagement` declaration

---

## Storybook Stories

- Stories live in `{name}.stories.tsx` alongside the component
- Every contract variant must have a corresponding named story
- Story names match contract variant `displayName` values exactly
- Contract metadata (description, usage do/dont, version) is piped into docs — never written by hand
- Interaction tests (`play` functions) required for any story involving user interaction
- All stories must pass a11y addon before merge
- `apps/web` and `apps/web-components` have separate Storybook instances — never merge them

---

## 90% parity — PR gate criteria

A component is ready for PR when all of the following pass:

1. All contract variants are implemented
2. Behavioral tests pass (interactions, states, keyboard navigation)
3. 0 a11y violations
4. Visual snapshot baseline established (Chromatic when active)
5. Token values match contract (ContractTokenTable shows no unresolved paths)

---

## Schema changes

- Update `packages/schema/schema.json` first
- Run `pnpm types:generate` to regenerate TypeScript types
- Document in `docs/decisions.md` as a new ADR
- Breaking changes (remove/rename fields) require a major version bump

---

## Versioning

- Use `pnpm changeset` to record changes before merging
- Never manually edit `CHANGELOG.md`

---

## CI

- All PRs must pass: `validate-contracts` → `build-tokens` → `test-web`
- Never merge with a failing CI run
- If you add a new package or app, add it to the CI workflow

---

## What not to do

- Don't write component CSS with raw values
- Don't create a component without a contract
- Don't write Storybook docs by hand
- Don't hand-roll keyboard navigation or focus management for complex components
- Don't merge contracts with `status: draft` without an implementation plan
- Don't skip `pnpm validate` before pushing contract changes
- Don't run Storybook without first building `@ds/contracts`
- Don't use `@component-contracts/` scope — always `@ds/`

## Icons

- The icon library is `@ds/icons` (planned — tracked in GitHub issues)
- Until `@ds/icons` exists, use **Lucide** as the icon provider across all web targets:
  - React: `lucide-react`
  - Web Components: `lucide-static`
- Never use one-off inline SVGs in component implementations — always use the icon library
- The `icon` contract (`ref: "icon"`) is the platform-agnostic spec — it doesn't care which library provides the icon
- When `@ds/icons` is built, Lucide is swapped out at the implementation layer — contracts do not change
- For native targets: iOS uses SF Symbols, Android uses Material Symbols as interim icon sources — document this in each component's `platformNotes`

---

## Fonts

- Font loading is owned by the token layer — never load fonts directly in component implementations, demo pages, or app entry points
- Always import `@ds/tokens/fonts` alongside `@ds/tokens/css`:
  ```ts
  import "@ds/tokens/css";
  import "@ds/tokens/fonts";
  ```
- `@ds/tokens/fonts` is the single place to update when the typeface changes
- For native targets: fonts are bundled per platform (Xcode project for iOS, `res/font/` for Android) — the token value tells you which font, the platform tells you how to load it
- Never add `<link>` tags for Google Fonts directly in HTML files — use the tokens fonts export instead